  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why isn't the U.S. doing more to combat Ebola?",
  "response": "The U.S. has been actively involved in combating the Ebola outbreak, both domestically and internationally. Here are some of the steps the U.S. has taken:\n\n1. **Funding and Aid:** The U.S. has provided significant financial and material aid to the affected regions. The U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) and other organizations have been working to provide medical supplies, training, and support to healthcare workers in West Africa.\n\n2. **Medical Teams and Facilities:** The U.S. has deployed medical teams and established treatment centers in affected countries. For instance, the U.S. military set up field hospitals in Liberia during the 2014-2016 outbreak.\n\n3. **Research and Development:** The U.S. has invested heavily in research for Ebola vaccines and treatments. The development of the Ebola vaccine rVSV-ZEBOV, which has been shown to be highly effective, was supported by U.S. funding.\n\n4. **Domestic Preparedness:** The U.S. has protocols in place for screening and treating Ebola patients within its borders. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and other health agencies have guidelines for managing potential cases and outbreaks.\n\n5. **Global Collaboration:** The U.S. works with international organizations like the World Health Organization (WHO) and other countries to coordinate efforts in combating Ebola.\n\nHowever, there are challenges and criticisms:\n\n1. **Resource Allocation:** Some argue that the U.S. could do more by allocating more resources to the affected regions, especially in terms of funding and personnel.\n\n2. **Political Will:** Public and political attention to global health crises can wane, affecting sustained commitment and funding.\n\n3. **Coordination Issues:** There can be challenges in coordinating efforts among various international actors, which may slow down response times and effectiveness.\n\n4. **Focus on Domestic Issues:** There's often a tension between focusing on domestic health issues versus international ones, which can influence policy decisions.\n\nIn summary, while the U.S. has been actively engaged in combating Ebola, there are ongoing debates about whether more could be done, and how best to balance domestic and international health priorities.",
